// The `prelude.json` sub-module: the `json` data type and its conversions. `json` is the tagged
// mirror of a JSON document — one `data` constructor per JSON shape, closed into the union synonym
// `json` — so a program can traverse an AI's reply with ordinary `match` arms. Referenced from user
// code by the default-import qualifier: type `json.json`, constructor patterns `json.json_object(...)`,
// conversions `json.parse(...)`.
//
// The conversions:
//
//   - `parse : string -> json`         the untyped text boundary (traverse the tree with `match`)
//   - `parse_as[T] : string -> T`      the TYPED text boundary — parse and validate against T's
//                                      schema in one step, no intermediate `json` tree
//   - `stringify[T] : T -> string`     any value to JSON text (a `json` value renders as the
//                                      document it stands for, so this inverts both parses)
//   - `encode[T] : T -> json`          embed a value into the `json` tree
//   - `decode[T] : json -> T`          read a tree back as a T, validated against T's schema
//
// The typed readers (`parse_as[T]` / `decode[T]`) are schema-directed: the call site's instantiation
// carries T's JSON Schema to the runtime (an inferred instantiation is stamped just like an explicit
// one), the document is validated against it, and a mismatch raises `panic` naming the offending
// path. T appears only in the result, so it is never inferable from the arguments — instantiate
// explicitly (`json.decode[my_type](...)`); an uninstantiated call is a compile error (K3016).
//
// `encode` embeds a value into its wire form: a record becomes `json_object` (a `data` value keeps
// its `$constructor` entry), an array `json_array`, a `file` its `$ref` handle object, an agent its
// `$agent` reference object; a value that is ALREADY `json` passes through unchanged, so a tool list
// mixing plain fields with schemas from `get_metadata` encodes correctly. A closure cannot be
// encoded (`panic`). A secret operand taints the whole result, which then may not cross a
// user-facing boundary — the usual monotonic information-flow rule.

@"A JSON null."
data json_null()
@"A JSON boolean."
data json_boolean(value: boolean)
@"A JSON number without a fractional part."
data json_integer(value: integer)
@"A JSON number."
data json_number(value: number)
@"A JSON string."
data json_string(value: string)
@"A JSON array."
data json_array(items: array[json])
@"A JSON object."
data json_object(entries: record[json])

// A JSON document: exactly one of the seven JSON shapes. (A `type` synonym carries no `@"..."`
// annotation; this comment is its documentation.)
type json = json_null | json_boolean | json_integer | json_number | json_string | json_array | json_object

@"Parse a JSON document from text into the `json` tree (traverse it with `match`). A malformed
document raises `panic`. A number without a fractional part parses as `json_integer`."
primitive agent parse(text: string) -> json

@"Parse a JSON document from text directly as a T, validated against T's schema — the typed text
boundary, with no intermediate `json` tree. Instantiate T explicitly (it appears only in the result,
so it cannot be inferred). A malformed document or a schema mismatch raises `panic` naming the
offending path."
primitive agent parse_as[T](text: string) -> T

@"Render any value as its (compact) JSON text — `stringify(value = json.encode(value = x))` in one
step, and the identity embedding on a value that is already `json`. A closure cannot cross the JSON
boundary and raises `panic`."
primitive agent stringify[T](value: T) -> string

@"Embed any value into `json`: records become `json_object` (a `data` value keeps its `$constructor`
entry), arrays `json_array`, scalars their JSON shape; a `file` becomes its `$ref` handle object and
an agent its `$agent` reference object. A value that is already `json` passes through unchanged. A
closure cannot cross the JSON boundary and raises `panic`."
primitive agent encode[T](value: T) -> json

@"Read a `json` tree back as a T, validated against T's schema (a `$constructor` entry re-tags a
`data` value; a missing tag is repaired when T pins exactly one). Instantiate T explicitly (it
appears only in the result, so it cannot be inferred) — `json.decode[unknown]` reads without a
shape. A mismatch raises `panic` naming the offending path; a `$agent` reference cannot be turned
back into a callable (`panic`)."
primitive agent decode[T](value: json) -> T
